    "## **The Problem: Customer Churn**\n",
    "\n",
    "A company say, a telecom or bank has thousands of customers. Some of them will eventually *leave* (cancel their subscription, close their account, stop buying). This is called **churn**. The company wants to know *which customers are about to leave* before they actually do, so they can take action offer a discount, assign a support rep, or reach out proactively.\n",
    "\n",
    "The challenge is that you cannot know for certain who will churn. You only have historical data about each customer: how long they've been with the company, how much they spend, how often they call support, what plan they're on, and so on.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "**What Kaggle is asking us to do**\n",
    "\n",
    "Kaggle has provided a synthetic (artificially generated but realistic) dataset of customer records. Each row in the training set is one customer, and we are told whether they churned or not (`Churn = 1` means they left, `Churn = 0` means they stayed).\n",
    "\n",
    "Our job is to build a model that looks at a *new* customer's data (in the test set, where the answer is hidden) and outputs a **probability** how likely is this customer to churn? A score of 0.9 means \"very likely to leave,\" 0.1 means \"very likely to stay.\"\n",
    "\n",
    "The competition scores us using **ROC-AUC**, which measures how well our model *ranks* churners above non-churners across all possible probability thresholds. A score of 1.0 is perfect; 0.5 is random guessing."
   ]
  },
