    "---\n",
    "## 3. Advanced Exploratory Data Analysis\n",
    "\n",
    "Exploratory data analysis is not a formality - it is where I discover the structure of the problem. I analyze:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Target distribution**: Understanding the class imbalance guides my choice of loss function, class weighting, and evaluation strategy.\n",
    "2. **Feature distributions**: I examine skewness, outliers, and modality to inform preprocessing.\n",
    "3. **Correlation analysis**: I identify highly correlated features that may cause multicollinearity in linear meta-models.\n",
    "4. **Train/Test distribution shift**: I compare feature distributions between training and test sets. If a feature exhibits significant drift (measured via KS statistic), it may be unreliable at inference time. Detecting drift early prevents me from over-engineering features that will hurt on the leaderboard.\n",
    "5. **Leakage checks**: I verify that no feature is trivially predictive of the target in an unrealistic way.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why ROC-AUC for imbalanced classification?**  \n",
    "With a churn rate that is typically in the 15–25% range, accuracy is a deceptive metric - a model that predicts \"no churn\" for every customer would achieve 80%+ accuracy. ROC-AUC measures the model's ability to rank churners above non-churners across all thresholds. It is invariant to class imbalance and rewards probability calibration.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why detecting train/test distribution shift is critical?**  \n",
    "Kaggle's synthetic datasets are generated with distribution shifts between train and test. A model that over-relies on drifted features will score well on CV but poorly on the public leaderboard. By computing KS statistics for each numerical feature, I can down-weight or remove problematic features."
   ]
  },
